No missing values observed and no imputations needed. If there are any missing values, recode to capture that information appropriately as a special value `-9` or where valid recode to max.

## Variable Selection

We run an XGBoost model to do the initial variable selection and reduce the predictor set. If there is a manual list of variables to throw out, include that in the blacklist below.






# Manual drop list
blacklist = ['badvar']

# Initial predictor set based on valid predictors
predictors = [c for c in valid_preds if c not in blacklist]

# Drop zero variance attributes
zero_variance = [c for c in predictors if data[c].var() == 0]
predictors_nz = [c for c in predictors if c not in zero_variance]

print(f'Total predictors : {len(predictors)}')
print(f'Zero variance    : {len(zero_variance)}')
print(f'Remaining        : {len(predictors_nz)}')




# Run an XGBoost model to reduce the predictor set
train_data = data[data['ind'] == 'train'].reset_index(drop=True)
test_data  = data[data['ind'] == 'test'].reset_index(drop=True)

train_dmat = xgb.DMatrix(
    train_data[predictors_nz],
    label         = train_data['perf'],
    weight        = train_data['wgt'],
    missing       = -9,
    feature_names = predictors_nz
)

test_dmat = xgb.DMatrix(
    test_data[predictors_nz],
    label         = test_data['perf'],
    weight        = test_data['wgt'],
    missing       = -9,
    feature_names = predictors_nz
)

params = {
    'eta'              : 0.1,   # slow learning
    'max_depth'        : 1,     # single depth for selection
    'min_child_weight' : 100,
    'objective'        : 'binary:logistic',
    'eval_metric'      : 'auc'
}

xgb_base = xgb.train(
    params                = params,
    dtrain                = train_dmat,
    num_boost_round       = 500,
    early_stopping_rounds = 10,
    evals                 = [(train_dmat, 'train'), (test_dmat, 'test')],
    verbose_eval          = False
)








## Feature Importance

Pick attributes contributing to 99% of cumulative gain.







importance = xgb_base.get_score(importance_type='gain')
base_features = (
    pd.DataFrame({
        'Feature' : list(importance.keys()),
        'Gain'    : list(importance.values())
    })
    .sort_values('Gain', ascending=False)
    .reset_index(drop=True)
)
base_features['Gain']     = base_features['Gain'] / base_features['Gain'].sum()
base_features['CumlGain'] = base_features['Gain'].cumsum()
base_features = base_features[base_features['CumlGain'] <= 0.99].reset_index(drop=True)

print(f'Reduced predictor set: {len(base_features)} attributes')

base_features.style \
    .format({'Gain': '{:.4f}', 'CumlGain': '{:.4f}'}) \
    .set_caption('Remaining attributes after variable reduction') \
    .hide(axis='index')







# Bin the top XGBoost predictors
bins = onecredit.optimal_binning(
    data        = data[data['ind'] == 'train'],
    model_vars  = base_features['Feature'].tolist(),
    target_name = 'perf',
    wgts_name   = 'wgt'
)

# Select the best of the binned variables
well_binned = [name for name, b in bins.items() if b.reject_code == 0]
print(f'Well-binned attributes: {len(well_binned)}')








# Consolidate drop list
drop_list = pd.concat([
    pd.DataFrame({'Attribute': blacklist,     'Reason': 'Blacklist'}),
    pd.DataFrame({'Attribute': zero_variance, 'Reason': 'Zero Variance'}),
    pd.DataFrame({'Attribute': [v for v in predictors
                                if v not in zero_variance
                                and v not in base_features['Feature'].tolist()],
                  'Reason': 'Failed XGB'}),
    pd.DataFrame({'Attribute': [name for name, b in bins.items() if b.reject_code != 0],
                  'Reason': 'Failed Binning'})
], ignore_index=True)

drop_list.style \
    .set_caption('Variables dropped in reduction') \
    .hide(axis='index')







# Final model variables after binning
model_vars = (
    base_features[base_features['Feature'].isin(well_binned)]
    .drop(columns='CumlGain')
    .reset_index(drop=True)
)

print(f'Final model variables: {len(model_vars)}')

model_vars.style \
    .format({'Gain': '{:.4f}'}) \
    .set_caption('Remaining attributes after variable reduction') \
    .hide(axis='index')








## Modifying the Bins Through Interactive Tool

The `merge_bins` function opens an interactive binning dashboard with two tabs:

1. **View Summary** — high level view of variables, trends and IV
2. **View Details** — variable level view allowing: neutralize bins, set monotonicity pattern, group bins, undo/redo

Click **Quit** to save changes. If window is cancelled without quitting, changes are not saved.

The above can also be done using `set_neutral` and `set_pattern` functions.

Saving the bins in a new variable keeps the original binning object in the environment.







